
After reading about Earth’s energy imbalance, I suddenly realized that I might have been confined within my own small world. After all, these issues are closely connected to every one of us. I deeply lament what humanity has done, and I have also come to understand that I am part of it all. Perhaps one day, when I am strong enough, I will be able to contribute. But even today, I can start with small things to reduce the burden I place on this planet.

I have also realized that I am still afraid of death. I do not know when I will leave this world, and I fear dying young—whether in my thirties, forties, fifties, or sixties. I sincerely hope that will never happen.

What’s more, many wealthy people today are screening their embryos for “superior genes,” determining intelligence and almost all traits before birth. But does humanity really think so highly of itself that it can replace the Creator?

These actions remind me of a saying: always remain reverent. Reverence is essential. If we lose our awe toward heaven, earth, nature, life, and death, it terrifies me.

Since ancient times, the wisdom of traditions has taught humanity the same truth. In Taoism, yin contains yang, and yang contains yin; Laozi and Zhuangzi urged us to follow nature and govern through non‑action. Buddhism speaks of balance and harmony. All these ancient philosophies reveal one thing: we cannot defy fate or reverse the laws of nature. We can only move in harmony with the way of things.

There is no absolute good or absolute bad in the world. As the saying goes, extreme joy begets sorrow.

Earlier, when I talked with an AI, it used a word that deeply unsettled me: mastery. Who are we to claim mastery over nature? Humans strive to climb the highest mountains and dive into the deepest oceans, believing they have conquered nature. Yet how many lives have been lost to this so‑called conquest?

We overestimate ourselves, thinking we are the masters of the Earth. Even the name reveals our arrogance: we call this planet “Earth,” even though it is three‑tenths land and seven‑tenths water. We cannot even control our own lives or deaths—so how dare we speak of mastery?
